The rules of probability theory
\[
\begin{align*}
P(A \vee B \mid \mathcal{I}) & =P(A \mid \mathcal{I})+P(B \mid \mathcal{I})-P(A, B \mid \mathcal{I}) & & \text { (sum rule) }, \\
P(A, B \mid \mathcal{I}) & =P(A \mid B, \mathcal{I}) P(B \mid \mathcal{I}) & & \text { (product rule) }, \\
1 & =P(A \mid \mathcal{I})+P(\bar{A} \mid \mathcal{I}) & & \text { (normalization) }, \\
P(A \mid \mathcal{I}) & =P(A, B \mid \mathcal{I})+P(A, \bar{B} \mid \mathcal{I}) & & \text { (marginalization rule). } \tag{1.8}
\end{align*}
\]
We use the convention that a comma between propositions stands for the logical ‘and’. Derivation and generalizations of the rules of probability theory will be discussed in Chapter 3 [p. 33]. Based on the commutativity of the logical ‘and’, we obtain \(P(A \mid B, \mathcal{I}) P(B \mid \mathcal{I})=P(B \mid A, \mathcal{I}) P(A \mid \mathcal{I})\) which immediately yields

MEAN OF A DISCRETE RANDOM VARIABLE
\[
\begin{equation*}
\langle X\rangle:=\sum_{n \in M} X_{n} P_{n} . \tag{2.1}
\end{equation*}
\]

Mean value of a function OF SEVERAL RANDOM VARIABLES
\[
\begin{equation*}
\left\langle f\left(X^{(1)}, \ldots, X^{(N)}\right)\right\rangle:=\sum_{n_{1} \in M_{1}} \cdots \sum_{n_{N} \in M_{N}} f\left(X_{n_{1}}^{(1)}, \ldots, X_{n_{N}}^{(N)}\right) P_{n_{1}, \ldots, n_{N}} . \tag{2.11}
\end{equation*}
\]
Example 2.3 The body mass index \((B M I)\) is defined as \(B M I=\frac{\text { mass in } \mathrm{kg}}{(\text { height in } \mathrm{m})^{2}}\). The average body mass index of the employees is given by the mean of the function \(f(m, h)=\frac{m}{h^{2}}\). This results in \(\langle f\rangle=23.9\).
An important characterization of multivariate stochastic problems is the covariance, which quantifies the correlation between two random variables.






Definition (Covariance) Given \(N\) discrete random variables as in Definition 2.10, the covariance of \(X^{(i)}\) and \(X^{(j)}\) is defined as

INDEPENDENT RANDOM VARIABLES
\[
\begin{equation*}
P_{n_{1}, n_{2}, \ldots, n_{N}}=\prod_{i=1}^{N} P_{n_{i}} . \tag{2.13}
\end{equation*}
\]
Consequently, the covariance of independent random variables is zero. Proof: For \(i \neq j\) we have
\[
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{cov}\left(X^{(i)} X^{(j)}\right) & =\left\langle X^{(i)} X^{(j)}\right\rangle-\left\langle X^{(i)}\right\rangle\left\langle X^{(i)}\right\rangle \\
& =\sum_{n_{1} \in M_{1}} \cdots \sum_{n_{N} \in M_{N}} X_{n_{i}}^{(i)} X_{n_{j}}^{(j)} \prod_{l=1}^{N} P_{n_{l}}-\left\langle X^{(i)}\right\rangle\left\langle X^{(i)}\right\rangle \\
& =\underbrace{\left(\sum_{n_{i} \in M_{i}} X_{n_{i}}^{(i)} P_{n_{i}}\right)}_{\left\langle X^{(i)}\right\rangle} \underbrace{\left(\sum_{n_{j} \in M_{j}} X_{n_{j}}^{(j)} P_{n_{j}}\right)}_{\left\langle X^{(i)}\right\rangle}-\left\langle X^{(i)}\right\rangle\left\langle X^{(j)}\right\rangle \\
& =\left\langle X^{(i)}\right\rangle\left\langle X^{(j)}\right\rangle-\left\langle X^{(i)}\right\rangle\left\langle X^{(j)}\right\rangle=0 .
\end{aligned}
\] \(\square\)

2.1.3 Generating functions
An important transformation of PMFs is the generating function, which is closely related to the characteristic functions used for continuous variables, which will be discussed along with the central limit theorem. The generating function of a PMF \(P_{n}\) for discrete events is defined by
Generating function
\[
\begin{equation*}
\phi(z):=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} P_{n} z^{n} . \tag{2.14}
\end{equation*}
\]

Moments of a probability distribution
The generating function is very powerful, as we will see in later chapters, because it allows for example, the generation of moments. In this context we specify the random variable by the index of the event, i.e. \(X_{n}=n\). Then
\[
\begin{align*}
\left.\phi(z)\right|_{z=1} & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} P_{n}  \tag{2.15a}\\
\left.\frac{d}{d z} \phi(z)\right|_{z=1} & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} n P_{n}  \tag{2.15b}\\
\left.\frac{d^{2}}{d z^{2}} \phi(z)\right|_{z=1} & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left(n^{2}-n\right) P_{n} . \tag{2.15c}
\end{align*}
\]
So we can determine the low-order moments as follows:
\[
\begin{align*}
\langle n\rangle & =\left.\frac{\frac{d}{d z} \phi(z)}{\phi(z)}\right|_{z=1}=\left.\frac{d}{d z} \log [\Phi(z)]\right|_{z=1},  \tag{2.16a}\\
\left\langle n^{2}\right\rangle & =\left.\frac{\frac{d^{2}}{d z^{2}} \phi(z)}{\phi(z)}\right|_{z=1}+\langle n\rangle  \tag{2.16b}\\
\left\langle(\Delta n)^{2}\right\rangle & =\left.\frac{d^{2}}{d z^{2}} \log [\Phi(z)]\right|_{z=1}+\langle n\rangle . \tag{2.16c}
\end{align*}
\]

Convolution of probability distributions
A structure that we will encounter frequently is convolutions. As a concrete example we consider an experiment in which photons stemming from a light source are counted. The measured signal, however, is affected by background radiation. In other words, the measured number of photons \(n\) is the sum of photons originating from signal \(n_{s}\) and background \(n_{b}\) :
\[
\begin{equation*}
n=n_{s}+n_{b} . \tag{2.17}
\end{equation*}
\]
Both counts are Poisson distributed with mean \(\mu_{s}\) and \(\mu_{b}\), respectively. The central question is: What is the distribution of the total count \(n\) ? Owing to equation (2.17), the total count can be obtained from \(n+1\) different pairs of exclusive realizations \(\left(n_{s}, n_{b}\right)= (n, 0),(n-1,1), \ldots,(0, n)\). According to the marginalization rule, the probability for the sum being \(n\) is
\[
\begin{aligned}
P\left(n \mid \mu_{s}, \mu_{b}, \mathcal{I}\right) & =\sum_{n_{s}, n_{b}=0}^{\infty} \underbrace{P\left(n \mid n_{s}, n_{b}, \mu_{s}, \mu_{b}, \mathcal{I}\right)}_{\delta_{n_{s}+n_{b}, n}} P\left(n_{s}, n_{b} \mid \mu_{s}, \mu_{b}, \mathcal{I}\right) \\
& =\sum_{n_{b}=0}^{\infty} P\left(n_{s}=n-n_{b} \mid \mu_{s}, \mathcal{I}\right) P\left(n_{b} \mid \mu_{b}, \mathcal{I}\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
We have used the fact that signal and background signals are uncorrelated. The first term actually restricts the sum to \(n_{b} \leq n\). The result is a convolution of the two PMFs. Generally, for two PMFs \(P_{\alpha}(n)\) the convolution \(C(n)\) is defined as

Convolution of two probability distributions
\[
\begin{equation*}
C(n):=\sum_{m=0}^{\infty} P_{1}(n-m) P_{2}(m) . \tag{2.18}
\end{equation*}
\]
Next we determine the generating function of the convolution by multiplying both sides by \(z^{n}\) and summing over \(n\) :
\[
\begin{aligned}
\Phi(z)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} C(n) z^{n} & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \sum_{m=0}^{\infty} z^{n-m} z^{m} P_{1}(n-m) P_{2}(m) \\
& =\left(\sum_{l=0}^{\infty} z^{l} P_{1}(l)\right)\left(\sum_{m=0}^{\infty} z^{m} P_{2}(m)\right) \\
& =\Phi_{1}(z) \Phi_{2}(z)
\end{aligned}
\]
The generating function of a convolution is therefore generally the product of the individual generating functions. This property will turn out to be very useful in various applications.

